<h2 id="comments">Comments</h2>

<div id="c1">
<p>Improved ecommerce for public benefit?</p>

<p>Someone with computer skills and leisure might take a look at a project that could make new business models feasible &#8212; especially for musicians, artists, and other small businesses selling digital content at low prices.</p>

<p>By lucky accident I explored possible uses for online financial accounts that could REPRODUCE through any number of generations, inherit many services, options, and methods through family trees, and evolve in community use. It&#8217;s new and appears revolutionary, but hasn&#8217;t received much attention.</p>

<p>My overview at www.smart-accounts.org may look too good to be true. But if it won&#8217;t work, then somebody who&#8217;s bright could figure that out quickly. I&#8217;ve looked for a showstopper for two years and haven&#8217;t found one.</p>

<p>This idea needs both commercial and open-source development. It should be available for all, not locked away in some corporation&#8217;s patent collection. I published it quietly for just that purpose, and have no proprietary claims.</p>

<p>John S. James, Philadelphia</p>

<p class="posted">posted by <a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.smart-accounts.org">John S. James</a>
 on April 24, 2007 <a href="#c1" rel="bookmark">#</a></p>
